                      in it dozens of times and many in rain and never once got wet.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The weight is pretty decent too, as is the pack size, especially for the money. It costs about
                      £160 (not
                      including a pole, if you want the luxe one that's an extra £30) and there really aren't many tents
                      for that
                      money that can compare in terms of their cost/weight/comfort intersection.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Also the reason there's no pole is you can theoretically set it up with trekking poles so you
                      might not
                      want one - many tents of this type come without one. however, this is a bigger tent than a lot of
                      other
                      trekking pole tents so it's touch-and-go. The optimal height for the Minipeak is supposed to be
                      140cm and
                      most trekking poles only go up to 135cm, but you can set it up at that and it should stay firm.
                      I bought the pole, though.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      All in all, I would highly recommend this tent.
