                  <div class="h5cont"><h5>3F Ultralight Gear Lanshan 1 Tent</h5></div>
                  <p>
                    A very good tent that a lot of people swear by. It's almost unbeatable (possibly literally so) in
                    the intersection
                    of weight and price. A two skin tent, it weighs in at just under 1Kg, and costs about £130 - it's
                    made in
                    China so the price can vary with exchange rates/import fees etc. There are UK sellers or you can buy
                    it
                    direct from 3UF.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    So cheaper and lighter than the Minipeak II then, and a not-inconsiderable weight saving at that, I
                    admit
                    that if I'm going to be walking distance with my pack on then this will probably be my pick.
                  </p>
                  <div id="lanshanExpand" class="collapse">
                    <p>
                      On the other hand, my preference is often to go camping for a few days and then go exploring from
                      that
                      campsite as a sort of basecamp. In this instance, I will almost always choose the Minipeak II.
                      Although
                      you wouldn't think it to look at them, the size difference is very noticeable from inside. The
                      inner
                      of the Lanshan is a bit wider than the Minipeak and you feel like you have a bit more room in
                      there,
                      but it's still hard to sit up in there. And conversely, the porch is much smaller. There's room to
                      sit
                      in there if it's raining (just) but it's pretty cramped even without taking into account all the
                      gear
                      you will undoubtedly have in the porch area. It's fine for sleeping in and storage though, so in
                      the depths of summer where rain is very unlikely, the weight savings may be worth the cost.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Another downside as compared to the Minipeak is the pitching. The Minipeak is incredibly easy to
                      pitch,
                      and yet despite being of similar (ish) design, this is not particularly. It's not too hard, but it
                      is pretty
                      hard to do well. It'll often end up leaning a bit more one way or the other, the doors too high
                      letting
                      wind in, or the whole pitch too low making it sag. Quite a pernickity pitcher.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      I'm also not sold on the waterproofing. It's supposed to be seam-sealed already, but I woke up one
                      morning
                      after rain with some water inside. It could've been condensation, but it was inside the inner so
                      it shouldn't
                      have been. The fabric is <em>very</em> light and thin though, so it's possible I tore a small hole
                      or pulled
                      a seam apart a bit when I was trying to get a good pitch. It's only happened once so far though,
                      so I'm not
                      sure if it's a problem yet.inipeakexpandlink:hover{
                      cursor: pointer;
                      text-decoration: underline;
                      /* CONTACT */


                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Overall I'd say if you're going to buy one of these tents, get the Minipeak II. However if you're
                      really really
                      desperate to shed weight, and especially to do so on a budget then this is still a good tent and
                      although
                      I prefer the Minipeak that's only because I have it to compare so I would still recommend this
                      tent for the
                      'light on a budget' crowd.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      But if you care about comfort as well, then the Minipeak is your pick. And it's not that heavy!
                    </p>
