                  <div class="h5cont"><h5>Gossamer Gear Mariposa 60 Litre Backpack</h5></div>
                  <p>
                    Review up front: I <em>love</em> this pack. It's probably my favourite piece of camping gear. It's
                    so
                    well designed, it's so comfortable to wear, you can get tons in it and it also carries very well
                    when
                    you don't have tons in it. It's also not massive, considering it's a 60 litre pack. The trick to
                    that is,
                    the main pack is only about 35l. This isn't a con, they tell you about it beforehand. It's all the
                    external
                    pockets that take it to 60l, and they are very well designed.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    This is another note in Gossamer Gears' favour - you're never really sure what you're getting with
                    other
                    manufacturers. Does the size count the pockets? How big are they anyway? But Gossamer Gear tell you
                    upfront.
                  </p>
                  <div id="mariposaExpand" class="collapse">
                    <p>
                      And the pockets are very clever. Unlike most packs, there's only one water-bottle pocket on a
                      single side,
                      but that pocket is massive and can easily accomodate two one-litre bottles, which is probably what
                      you would
                      get in two pockets on most other bags. The reason it only has one pocket like this is that on the
                      other side
                      is the very clever 'quiver' pocket. This is basically a water bottle pocket on steroids. It starts
                      at the
                      of the pack and the top is about half way up the pack. It's designed to carry things like tent
                      poles and other
                      long objects safely, and is very, very clever. If I ever got a different pack I think this is the
                      feature I'd
                      miss the most. And of course you can put other things in there. I tend to put my long items in
                      first, and
                      then pack smaller stuff sacks in where there's room. The one proviso is of course that it's open
                      to the elements
                      so you will need waterproof bags.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      In more making-good-use-of-space news, there's another pocket above the water bottle pocket for...
                      Well, whather,
                      I suppose. I keep my stove and pot in there so I can make tea when I'm walking without digging
                      through my pack,
                      but I imagine it could have any number of useful applications.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      And then comes the big mesh pocket on the back. Lots of packs have this, of course. I would
                      seriously hesistate
                      to buy one that didn't. But this is a particularly fine example. It has a flat bottom, loose mesh,
                      and then a
                      tight top. The first two means that it's <em>massive</em> and you can fit so much stuff in there -
                      the loose
                      mesh means you can put quite a bit in before it's even really stretching, but then the tight top
                      means it would be very difficult to lose things out of it, even when there's a lot in there. The
                      mesh is also
                      quite dense when compared to other similar pockets so which still a weak point (probably the
                      weakest) on
                      the pack, it's still hardier than you would think.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Structurally, the pack has a removable frame inside. The frame is basically two solid tubes of
                      metal about 5mm
                      in diameter. It does a pretty good job of weight transfer - not as good as something more
                      substantial, but
                      for the weight of the pack I doubt you will find better.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      And on that note, the entire pack comes in at under 1Kg. For a 60l pack that is comfortable up to
                      30lbs (13.5Kg)
                      and rated to go to 35lbs I find this weight exceptional. I say under 1Kg, but I think my version
                      is under 900g -
                      I have the older model and I think it got a little bit heavier. It's still under 1Kg though, I
                      believe.
                      And that weight includes the very substantial and comfortable hip belt - which you can remove - as
                      well as the
                      frame. Also, the frame slots directly into the hip belt, make for much better load transfer than
                      if it didn't,
                      which I thought was nice design touch.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Incidentally, while both are removable, you can use the pack without the frame but with the hip
                      belt, but the
                      reverse is not true - you cannot use the frame without the hip belt (since it slots in). The hip
                      belt is another
                      piece of design I love about this pack. The pockets, one either side, are simply <em>massive</em>.
                      You can easily
                      fit a smartphone (or three) in there along with all manner of other goodies. The padding on the
                      back of the
                      pockets is extremely thick and extremely comfortable. I haven't had tons of packs, but this is by
                      far the
                      most comfortable hip belt I've experienced. It also comes in several different sizes from 'very
                      skinny person' to
                      'very overweight person' and this is independent of the pack size - you can buy the medium pack
                      with the extra large
                      hip belt if that's your body type. This was a big selling point to my overweight self, and I'm
                      sure it would be to
                      lots of other people since normally the hip belt scales with the pack like we all have the same
                      body type.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      And now the only real downside. The price. I'm only aware of <a
                        href="https://ultralightoutdoorgear.co.uk/mariposa-60-rucksack/">one retailer</a>
                      in the UK that sells this pack, and it currently costs £310. Ouch. It was quite a bit cheaper when
                      I bought
                      it, and there were other options (two EU websites who are no longer as cheap as they once were in
                      a
                      post-Brexit world). So that's unfortunate. That being said... I would still recommend this pack,
                      at least
                      to the right person. I wouldn't buy it to go camping once obviously, but if you think you're going
                      to go a
                      bunch and it's time to upgrade from the £40 Amazon pack that ways 2Kg, and of course if you can
                      afford it,
                      then I'm honestly not sure there's a better rucksack than this one in existence.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The intersection of weight, design, comfort, sturdiness and useability is simply unmatched. Just a
                      shame
                      about the price!
                    </p>
                  </div>
