                    <div class="h5cont"><h5>Big Agnes VNotch UL 40 Sleeping Bag</h5></div>
                    <p>
                      Synthetic or down? The ultimate hiker's conundrum. Down is a natural substance from birds (a layer
                      under the feathers) and when put into a jacket or sleeping bag it lofts up and traps warm air and
                      keeps you very warm. And then when you're done it compresses down really, really small and is very
                      lightweight so it's easy to pack and carry.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Synthetic insulation, on the other hand, is generally heavier and less compressible. It's
                      improving all
                      the time and mostly it seems to do that by clever people trying to make synthetic fibres that
                      closely mimic
                      down.
                    </p>

                    <div id="vnotchExpand" class="collapse">

                      <p>
                        So with that being the case, you would choose down, right? It's lighter, warmer, and more
                        compressible.
                        These are very obviously things you want in a sleeping bag you're going to carry for miles at a
                        time.
                        So there no contest, right?
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Well of course there is. Down doesn't work when it's wet. Like, at all. When the fibres get wet,
                        they clump
                        up and don't loft and if they don't loft they don't insulate. At all. And wow, I wonder if a
                        sleeping bag
                        might get wet in average UK weather? And wet doesn't just mean rain by the way. All tents will
                        have some
                        form of condensation on the inside at some point, not to mention human beings sweat, sweat makes
                        things
                        wet and your sleeping bag gets pretty close to your body... which you sweat from.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        As with synthetic fibres, a lot of progress has been made in treating down - giving it
                        waterproofing (or
                        resistance, at least) so some bags as long as they're not completely soaked will still function.
                        And then
                        there's the option of making the bag from waterproof material, of course. But it still seems
                        like a risk to
                        me.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Don't get me wrong, a lot of people choose down. Most, maybe. But living in the UK I just don't
                        see it as the
                        smart choice. Your bag will get wet eventually and maybe a modern down bag will hold up and
                        maybe it won't
                        but I know a synthetic bag will still have at least some warmth when wet and when it comes to
                        something that
                        could literally save your life, my personal opinion is - why take the chance?
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        So I would rather carry the extra weight for the peace of mind. Plus there's the benefit that a
                        decent down
                        bag is going to be <em>very</em>expensive, and a decent synthetic bag will range from
                        not-too-expensive to
                        a bit expensive.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Except this one. This one is quite expensive (still not compared to down) and also quite
                        lightweight (but
                        not really compared to down). The bag weighs under 600g, costs about £180 and is rated to 40°F
                        (4°C)
                        although these ratings are just a guide and will vary from person to person. I've personally
                        used it at
                        0°C wearing just a thermal baselayer and was never cold. At under 600g for a synthetic bag, that
                        is
                        exceptional. For down comparison, a good bag rated for the same temperature would probably
                        weight about
                        200g less and cost anywhere from the same to £100 more. And then there would be some that would
                        cost
                        even more than that. Sleeping bags costing more than £500 are not undheard of.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        I am unaware of any synthetic bag that can match this one for compressibility, weight and
                        warmth.
                        I do consider it on the pricier side but in the end I decided it was probably worth it for the
                        weight
                        saving so I saved up (and of course not camping for two years of the pandemic was helpful here).
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Whether you choose down or synthetic is up to you, I can only tell you my choice, but if
                        synthetic is the
                        way you want to go then you would be hard-pressed to find a better bag than this.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        My only complaint other than the price (which isn't really a complaint since obviously I knew
                        what it
                        cost when I bought it) is that the zipper will often get snagged on the material. it's
                        inevitable really
                        the first place almost all manufacturers go to save weight on a bag is the zip, so this has a
                        tiny
                        little dinky thin one which I think is the problem. You can always sort it out though, it's
                        never
                        been what I would consider a real problem, just an annoyance.
                      </p>

