                      <div class="gearTextLeft">
                        <div class="h5cont"><h5>Gram Counter Gear Crash Out Sleeping Mat</h5></div>
                        <p>
                          A very good mat with regards to the intersection of price and weight. Mostly only for the
                          warmer months,
                          but let's be honest, that's when most of us camp anyway.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                          The Thermarest NeoAir X-Lite has become the gold standard benchmark for ultralight hikers the
                          world over
                          due to its incredibly light weight (although Thermarest have since released the even-lighter
                          Uberlight,
                          although questions remain about this product's sturdiness), and yet this mat comes in at about
                          20g lighter
                          and at half to two-thirds the price (the X-lite can vary wildly in price, but expect to pay
                          £120-£180. The
                          Crash Out Mat costs £60 at
                          <a href="https://ultralightoutdoorgear.co.uk/crash-out-mat/">Ultralight Outdoor Gear</a>, the
                          only UK retailer
                          for Gram Counter Gear that I'm aware of.

                        <div id="crashoutExpand" class="collapse">

                          </p>
                          <p>
                            Half the price, for the same (or slightly less) weight? So what's the catch, you might be
                            thinking. Well, you'd
                            be right to. At least, there's a difference in the mats, although not so much a catch. The
                            difference is that
                            the Crash Out Mat has no insulation at all, where the NeoAir has quite a lot. I suppose
                            people who don't camp
                            think a sleeping mat is just for comfort - I did - but it incredibly isn't.
                          </p>
                          <p>
                            The first step in understanding the importance of sleeping mats is knowing that sleeping
                            bags
                            (and insulated jackets) work by having
                            "puffy things" inside - such as down or a synthetic down-mimicking insulation - that lofts
                            up and traps lots of nice
                            warm air between fibres. However, the lofting up is the crucial bit, so this type of
                            insulation will not
                            work when it's compressed i.e. the bottom of a sleeping bag with your body weight on it.
                            This is why a
                            lot of ultralight hikers favour quilts - they are lighter, and having insulated material
                            beneath you is
                            essentially a waste since it will not insulate anything when compressed.
                          </p>
                          <p>
                            The second thing to know is that when laying on the ground, you lose a lot more heat to the
                            cold ground through conduction than you do to the
                            air. Add to that the fact you have a sleeping bag preventing you from losing heat to the air
                            that does very
                            little to prevent you from losing heat to the ground and you should now be seeing the
                            importance of a layer
                            between you and the ground.
                          </p>
                          <p>
                            So basically the NeoAir X-Lite has enough insulated (a 4.5 R-value. You can google that if
                            you want to know)
                            that it should basically be fine all year round sleeping at sea level (i.e. not up a
                            mountain) in the south
                            of the UK. The Crash Out Mat, on the other hand, has no insulation at all, so what does this
                            mean?
                          </p>
                          <p>
                            Well, the act of raising you off the floor with a cusion of air beneath you will save you
                            from quite a lot
                            of heat loss regardless of added insulation. So this pad is definitely fine for camping the
                            the UK summer and
                            probably much of the spring and autumn as well. I would probably look at the weather
                            forecast and if it were
                            forecast to go no lower that 5°C then I would feel comfortable taking this mat (with an
                            appropriate sleeping
                            bag of course). Although that's just my personal feeling, and I do sleep quite warm -
                            everyone sleeps at a
                            different temperature (and men generally sleep warmer than women) so really the only way to
                            know what works for
                            you is to try different things.
                          </p>
                          <p>
                            So in conclusion, this mat is <em>great</em>for everything other than 'fairly cold' and
                            below. And honestly I'm
                            aware of nothing that can match its price/weight intersection. So if you're mostly a
                            summer/warmer camper then
                            I can definitely recommend this mat.
                          </p>
                          <p>
